         <h1>Bob Flanagan, 43, Performer Who Fashioned Art From His Pain </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Bob Flanagan , a performance artist and poet whose writing and bizarre , sadomasochistic performances centered on his lifelong battle with an incurable illness , died on Thursday at Long Beach Memorial Hospital in Long Beach . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 43 and lived in Los Angeles . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was cystic fibrosis , said his companion and collaborator , Sheree Rose . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Flanagan was said by doctors to be one of the longest-living survivors of cystic fibrosis , which is genetic and usually kills before adulthood . <br><blue>5</blue>An older sister , Patricia , died of cystic fibrosis in 1979 at the age of 21 . <br><blue>6</blue>A former cystic fibrosis poster boy , Mr. Flanagan recalled that he grew up being told that he had only a few years to live . <br><blue>7</blue>And he attributed his longevity in part to his ability to " fight pain with pain , " by which he meant that he took control of his suffering through the ritualized pain of sadomasochism . <br><blue>8</blue>In time , he made his art out of this proclivity . <br><blue>9</blue>His work related to the often painful performances of such early 1970 's body artists as Chris Burden , Arnold Schwarzkogler and Carolee Schneemann . <br><blue>10</blue>Mr. Flanagan 's work was the subject of a disturbing exhibition at the New Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo in the fall of 1994 . <br><blue>11</blue>Mr. Flanagan was born in New York City on Dec. 26 , 1952 , and grew up in Glendora , Calif. , a suburb of Los Angeles . <br><blue>12</blue>He had little formal art training but began painting as a teen-ager and then switched to poetry . <br><blue>13</blue>He studied literature at California State University , Long Beach , and at the University of California at Irvine . <br><blue>14</blue>After moving to Los Angeles in 1976 , he became involved with Beyond Baroque , an alternative literary center in Los Angeles , where he gave readings of autobiographical poems about his illness and his sex life . <br><blue>15</blue>In 1978 he published the first of five books of poetry and prose , " The Kid Is a Man . " <br><blue>16</blue>He also worked as a stand-up comic with the Groundlings , an improvisational theater group that included Pee-wee Herman . <br><blue>17</blue>His readings and comedy routines gradually evolved into performances involving masochistic acts in which Ms. Rose , a video artist and dominatrix with whom he worked for the last 15 years , participated . <br><blue>18</blue>The New Museum show , first organized by the Santa Monica Museum of Art , was Mr. Flanagan 's only exhibition and it generated widespread debate about its claim to be art . <br><blue>19</blue>In it , he displayed sculptures , videos and also spent time in a hospital bed in the middle of the gallery , talking to visitors . <br><blue>20</blue>In addition to Ms. Rose , he is survived by his parents , Mr. and Mrs. Robert C. Flanagan , who live in Arizona , and a brother , John . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>His work</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan 's work</m_str> (10_1) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Long Beach</m_str> (1_35) 	<m_str>Long Beach</m_str> (13_9) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>an incurable illness</m_str> (1_22) 	<m_str>his illness</m_str> (14_32) 	<br><blue>4(4)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (19_2) 	<m_str>The New Museum show , first organized by the Santa Monica Museum of Art</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (18_23) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (18_28) 	<br><blue>5(12)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (7_9) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_12) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_28) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_18) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_2) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_4) 	<m_str>A former cystic fibrosis poster boy , Mr. Flanagan</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_21) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_4) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_24) 	<br><blue>6(22)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (15_3) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_18) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan 's</m_str> (18_17) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_25) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_4) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan 's</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_32) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan</m_str> (6_8) 	<m_str>The Kid</m_str> (15_16) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_35) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_9) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_25) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_8) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Flanagan</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (20_11) 	<br><blue>7(5)</blue>: <m_str>Glendora , Calif. , a suburb of Los Angeles</m_str> (11_19) 	<m_str>Los Angeles</m_str> (14_4) 	<m_str>Los Angeles</m_str> (14_21) 	<m_str>Los Angeles</m_str> (11_26) 	<m_str>Los Angeles</m_str> (2_7) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
